		<h2>Anxiety and Panic Disorder</h2>
		<p>Inability to let go of worries, incessant chattering, obsessive and compulsive behaviors are all systemic of underlining and deep rooted anxiety.  Many children express anxious feelings in different ways, tantrums, avoidance and dissociation, inability to let go of thoughts, overwhelming urges, self-harm (picking, scratching), repetitive behaviors, and verbal expression. Anxiety can come from a variety of internal and external cues, regardless of how they came about, the brain changes in response to the stress.</p> 

		<p>Balancing neurotransmitters can help attain a calm, children who have never felt settled can finally turn down the “volume” in their brains.   The correct ratios between neurotransmitters, specifically the excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmitters is effective in providing the brain with the support it needs to combat the anxiety symptoms.  In many of the neurotransmitter panels that we have completed there is a higher level of excitatory neurotransmitters than inhibitory neurotransmitters.  As you can imagine, any excitatory input can easily push a child who is already sensitive. Neurotransmitter balancing is considered to be a long-term, effective solution.</p>
